---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Expertise" description="Platform Engineering, AI Governance, Enterprise IT Architecture — focus areas of Michael Linder.">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 py-16 md:py-24">
    <h1 class="font-display text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight md:text-4xl">Expertise</h1>

    <div class="mt-12 space-y-16">

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">Platform Engineering & GitOps</h2>
        <div class="prose mt-4">
          <p>
            Platforms that make developer teams productive instead of burdening them with infrastructure complexity — that's what I've been working on for over two decades. Today, that means GitOps-based delivery pipelines with ArgoCD, Helm Charts, Tekton, and Infrastructure as Code. The tools change, the goal stays the same: reproducible, traceable, secure deployments that work even when the incident alert fires at three in the morning.
          </p>
          <p>
            My approach is spec-driven. Before a line of code is written, the specification exists — not as a bureaucratic exercise, but as a thinking tool. Those who write down what a system should do first end up building fewer systems that don't.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">AI Governance & EU AI Act</h2>
        <div class="prose mt-4">
          <p>
            The EU AI Act has been in force since 2024, and many DACH enterprises — particularly SMEs — are facing the question of what it concretely means for them. Not every company builds AI models, but almost every company uses AI-based tools. The responsibility for what these tools do does not rest with the vendor alone.
          </p>
          <p>
            My focus lies on the bridge between technical architecture and regulatory compliance: risk assessments for AI systems, documentation requirements, governance structures that fit into existing organisations, and the honest assessment of where an SME needs to act and where it doesn't. No compliance theatre — workable solutions.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">Enterprise IT Architecture</h2>
        <div class="prose mt-4">
          <p>
            Over twenty years in enterprise IT means: having seen systems that work and systems that don't. The difference is rarely in the technology and almost always in the architecture decision someone made three years ago. My cross-section spans from .NET backends to cloud infrastructure (Azure, AWS) to M365 ecosystems, from DevOps pipelines to security architecture.
          </p>
          <p>
            What sets me apart is not the breadth alone, but the ability to find the three places in an existing system where a change has the greatest leverage — and the two places where it's better to leave things alone.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
